{{Infobox organization | name = Instytut Adama Mickiewicza | logo = Adam Mickiewicz Institute logo (English).jpg | type = Cultural institution | founded_date = {{start date and age|2000|03|01|df=yes}} | founder = [[Polish Government]] | location = ''ulica Mokotowska 25'' (the [[Sugar Palace]]), [[Warsaw]] | origins = | key_people = Paweł Potoroczyn, <small>Director</small> | area_served = 20 countries, worldwide | product = Polish [[Culture of Poland|cultural]] and [[Polish language|language]] education | focus = | method = | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | subsid = | owner = | Non-profit_slogan = | homepage = [http://www.iam.pl www.iam.pl] | dissolved = | footnotes = }} [[File:Miod14DSC 1246.jpg|thumb|260px|Adam Mickiewicz Institute (housed in the "[[Sugar Palace]]"), Warsaw]] The '''Adam Mickiewicz Institute''' ({{lang-pl|Instytut Adama Mickiewicza}}) is a government-sponsored organization funded by [[Poland]]'s [[Ministry of Culture and National Heritage (Poland)|Ministry of Culture and National Heritage]], and headquartered at ''ulica Mokotowska 25'' (the [[Sugar Palace]]) in [[Warsaw]].
Named after Polish [[List of national poets#Europe|national poet]] [[Adam Mickiewicz]], its goal is to promote the [[Polish language]] and [[Culture of Poland|Polish culture]] abroad.<ref>[http://www.iam.pl/en/about-us/about-the-institute Adam Mickiewicz Institute: About us] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212025613/http://www.iam.pl/en/about-us/about-the-institute |date=February 12, 2013 }}</ref> The Institute operates a bilingual Polish-English portal, "Culture.pl", founded in 2001.
==Activities== Besides a large number of associated poets, essayists, writers, translators, artists; literary, music, and film critics; and curators, the Institute includes Paweł Potoroczyn (director),<ref name="Potoroczyn">{{cite web|url=http://www.iam.pl/en/about-us/structure/director.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130705192621/http://www.iam.pl/en/about-us/structure/director.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-07-05 |title=Director: Paweł Potoroczyn |publisher=Instytut Adama Mickiewicza |date=2013 |accessdate=2013-05-09 |author=IAM }}</ref> [[editor-in-chief]] Weronika Kostyrko, and editors Mikołaj Gliński (literature), Filip Lech (music), Anna Legierska (theatre), Bartosz Staszczyszyn (film), and Agnieszka Sural (visual arts).<ref name="O nas">{{cite web | url=http://www.culture.pl/o-nas | title=Culture.pl editorial board | publisher=Instytut Adama Mickiewicza | work=Culture.pl "O nas" | date=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-09 | author=Culture.pl | format=names, contact info}}</ref>
In addition to the Ministry-of-Culture-sponsored Adam Mickiewicz Institute, there are Polish Cultural Institutes, sponsored by the [[Polish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msz.gov.pl/Instytuty,Polskie,20909.html |title=Instytuty Polskie |publisher=Msz.gov.pl |date= |accessdate=2012-05-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216225043/http://www.msz.gov.pl/Instytuty%2CPolskie%2C20909.html |archivedate=2012-02-16 }}</ref> in over 22 major foreign cities, including [[Berlin]], [[Bratislava]], [[Budapest]], [[Bucharest]], [[Düsseldorf]], [[Kiev]], [[Leipzig]], [[London]], [[Minsk]], [[Moscow]], [[New York City]], [[Paris]], [[Prague]], [[Rome]], [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Sofia]], [[Stockholm]], [[Tel Aviv]], [[Vienna]], and [[Vilnius]].
While the Adam Mickiewicz Institute frequently collaborates with the Polish Cultural Institutes, each institution is independent of the other and is sponsored by a different Polish government ministry.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101230021524/http://www.culture.pl/en/culture/instytucje/instytuty_polskie Polish Cultural Institutes around the world - arranged according to cities in an alphabetical order.] Internet Archive. Retrieved May 9, 2013.</ref>
